                            <comment id="12363856" author="davidvc" created="Wed, 25 Jan 2006 03:36:41 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;XN401 - XN450&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12377302" author="davidvc" created="Tue, 2 May 2006 08:23:33 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;This patch resolves this issue.  A couple of things to note:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul class=&quot;alternate&quot; type=&quot;square&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In some areas  made some significant changes to the message text, as in many cases it was overly verbose and abstruse.  Please see if you like the changes I made&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;


&lt;ul class=&quot;alternate&quot; type=&quot;square&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;I modified SQLExceptionFactory to handle DRDA-specified SQL States that indicate a feature is not supported, a connection exception, or a transaction rollback.  Take a look and see what you think&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;


&lt;p&gt;Please review.  derbyall passes and jdbc40 passes. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12377471" author="kmarsden" created="Wed, 3 May 2006 04:56:38 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Could you elaborate on this item:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul class=&quot;alternate&quot; type=&quot;square&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;I modified SQLExceptionFactory to handle DRDA-specified SQL States that indicate a feature is not supported, a connection exception, or a transaction rollback.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;


&lt;p&gt;Were there specific SQLStates or ErrorCodes were changed?&lt;br/&gt;
If so, what are the old and new values?&lt;br/&gt;
What behaviour changes would users see as the result of this patch?&lt;/p&gt;

</comment>
                            <comment id="12377472" author="davidvc" created="Wed, 3 May 2006 05:09:04 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Hi, Kathey.  In those rare cases in the network client where SqlException already has something besides null for SQLState (which only was happening when DRDA had a required specific SQL State), I have not changed those SQL States.  They are still consistent with the spec, as are the error codes.  The only thing that has changed in some cases are the error messages, as our messages were just too abstruse and cloaked in DRDA-speak.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;SQLExceptionFactory40 is responsible for throwing the right subclass of SQLException based on the type of error.  It does this by looking at the SQLState.  Previously it did not handle SQLStates as defined by DRDA, many of which indicate a connection exception or a warning, both of which have specific SQLException subclasses associated with them.   So I modified SQLExceptionFactory40 to handle the DRDA-specified SQLStates.  This ensures that the right subclass is thrown and that application code that is looking for a particular subclass gets it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;David&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="12377584" author="andreask" created="Wed, 3 May 2006 22:12:52 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;In my review comments posted on derbydev, I commented on the error message:&lt;br/&gt;
ERROR 08004: Connection authorization failure occurred.  Reason: userid invalid.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;My comments were to change the message due to security policy reason, and to rephrase. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thank you for including this into the committed patch. However, I think this change additionally required another master file to be updated &lt;br/&gt;
(java/testing/org/apache/derbyTesting/functionTests/master/DerbyNetClient/dataSourcePermissions_net.out)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.multinet.no/~solberg/public/Apache/TinderBox_Derby/testlog/SunOS-5.10_i86pc-i386/399165-derbyall_diff.txt&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;http://www.multinet.no/~solberg/public/Apache/TinderBox_Derby/testlog/SunOS-5.10_i86pc-i386/399165-derbyall_diff.txt&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Note: I have reviewed the committed patch , and found no other issues.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
